The first preliminary results of the early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday resulted in a noticeable weakening of the two parties of the so-called Great Coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖRP), where the current President Wilhelm Molterer's position was seriously shaken, suffered a particularly strong loss.
On the other hand, the President of the Association for the Future of Austria (BZÖ) and the provincial magistrate of Carinthia, Jörg Haider, are preparing to return to national politics.
Based on preliminary results, the country's strongest party remains the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) with 29.8 percent of the votes, but it lost 5.5 percent of the votes compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse was the ÖVP, which loses almost nine percent of the votes by 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of both major parties in Austria's post-war history, and in particular, the result is literally disastrous for the People's Party that has brought about early elections.
At the beginning of July, when leaving the ÖVP coalition, the People's Party had a significant advantage for SPÖ, according to public opinion polls.
But the voters apparently punished him for letting the government fail.
The first reactions to the results were speculation about the possible resignation of the party president Wilhelm Molterer and the current vice chancellor.
The observers believe that this could already take place on Monday at the extraordinary meeting of the Party Presidency.
This development would probably facilitate an increasingly likely way out of the election result, i.e. the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP Grand Coalition.
In view of the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Austrian Freedom Party (FPÖ) had previously acquired 18 percent of the votes and the BZÖ had 11 percent of the votes - but the Social Democrats also expressed fear of the repetition of 1999 when the People's Party agreed on joint governance with the populists (the FPÖ was still united at the time, leaving the BZÖ in 2005), which even brought about sanctions on the part of the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to cooperate with any party, and I assume that he can return to Vienna in national politics, is obviously expecting this solution.
The Green Party has also reached Parliament, which has slightly lost its popularity, and has fallen from third to fifth among Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties exceeded the four-percent limit and did not reach Parliament.
