Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey's intention to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps from the European border, is one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neorenaissance style.
At least that's what the guidebooks say.
The building surrounds the end of the platforms with a tower at each of the front corners, and it looks like some German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building's a little rocky.
However, in view of the interior of the vaulted ticket office, it is obvious what a large enterprise this was the westernmost gate.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, the "later future" of conquests, intended to achieve the ambitions of the Middle East through this railway leading from Damascus through Baghdad to Saudi Arabia today.
The German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
Relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and expelled the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria.
Hyderpasha Station didn't do any better.
In 1917 an munitions train exploded and destroyed the nicely designed roof of the building.
According to the Turkish sources, there's been an act of sabotage.
Since then, it's been slowly ruined, and history has gone far beyond.
At the same time, today, as the gateway to Anatolia and the entire Eastern region, it serves as an expanding diplomatic horizon for Turkey, at least in a symbolic sense.
The Justice and Development Party on the government - the AKP - has developed a whole new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The new policy is marked by commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian groups of Hamas and Fatah, Iraq, Iran and, of course, the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to assess the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I took the night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the leading foreign policy experts of the AKP, the Turkish Member of Parliament, Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, after about ten and a half hours of zötszöszön, which at the time gave me the rhythm of the famous documentary about the old world, "The Night Mail" - I arrived in the Turkish capital. The new city is intended as a symbol of the new secular state, which turns its back on the past atom.
However, the AKP, known to have Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This caused some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern building made of stone and steel, specially designed for this purpose - standing in a developing suburb between semi-finished shopping centres and cafés. In the latter, the middle managers in suits meet - both men and women - to make a deal early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have fit a right-to-centre politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit, a tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
"The party's foreign policy objective is to assist Turkey's reintegration into its immediate environment.
The Cold War upset the order," he said.
Turkey is isolated from its hinterland.
Today he had to turn east and west at the same time.
He couldn't choose between the two.
He had to open both ways.
"But is it possible that sooner or later you'll be forced to choose?" I asked.
"Turkey never wanted to come to a crossroads."
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to here almost mechanically repeated: Turkey's relations with not only the Middle East but also with the Caucasus and the countries surrounding the Black Sea benefit Europe and the United States as well as Turkey itself.
It is as if they want to convey the message that, figuratively, the whole of Europe, together with Turkey, will be able to reach Asia and the Middle East on those east railways.
When I was back at the Hydarpasha station, after another largely awake night, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conura, the two German gentlemen who watched the recovery of this fancy structure 100 years ago.
How they would have wondered to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East are now largely in Turkey's hands.
And as I waited at the port for the ferry to take me back through the Bosporus, I remembered that Turkey was once called "the sick man of Europe".
At least at the time, there was no question of which continent to claim this exciting country.
