The crash avoider is a beehive.
For the development of anti-accident technologies, Nissan this time was inspired by nature, precisely from the world of bees, for its new invention.
The Japanese company designed a robot that avoids accidents by imitating the fly of bees.
The Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C may be the first step in developing collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center, in cooperation with the renowned Tokyo University's Advanced Research and Technology Research Centre, built this small robot in Japan.
Kazuhiro Doi, Director of the Technology PR and Research and Development Brand, defined BR23C as a further extension of Nissan's four-level safety cover.
The robot enhances the ability of the company's products to avoid collision.
During flight, each bee develops its oval - shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety envelope.
However, the role of the complex eye of the uterus is much more important, with which it can see at an angle of more than 300 degrees in each direction. Consequently, the uterus can fly smoothly in its own personal space.
To copy the function of the composite eye, engineers designed a so-called Laser Range Finder.
The instrument shall identify the obstacles in a 180-degree field of vision before the BR23C, calculate their distance, and send a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which shall immediately be converted into an action to avoid collision.
"As soon as the barrier is detected, the small robot, imitating the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at smaller or larger angles to avoid collision.
The main difference between the system and the instruments currently available is that in this case the avoidance manoeuvre is carried out completely automatically.
If not, the robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
In a way other than bees, the manoeuvring manoeuvre shall not be directed upwards or downwards, nor diagonally, but only in two dimensions, and only in the direction of wheel rotation, i.e. not in infinite directions and ways, as is the case with bees.
Therefore, Nissan also used a rotation function in addition to acceleration and deceleration in the robot to avoid collisions.
"This device only has to process and react to the data every few seconds.
There is no need for data storage or intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can operate without interruption with only a few dozen KB memories.
This may sound surprising, but it's not gigabyte, but we're not even talking about megabyte-sized memories.
This is the first step towards the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which, according to Nissan's estimates, can enter mass-produced cars within ten years.
The robot operates with lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system could be an additional option to get the driver to the final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
