Rafael Correa's Monday statement, Quito
Rebuilding the Republic in the spirit of 21st century socialism.
This is the joint plan for Hugo Chávez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
Following the model of his fellow presidents and friends, Correa presented his ideas on the new constitution on Sunday.
He succeeded in his mission, as 64% of the voters voted in favour of the referendum according to official results, which concerned 80% of the votes.
According to this, 28% of the population voted no, 7% of the votes were invalid, while 0.7% of the votes were unfilled.
The adoption of the draft Constitution required 50% + 1 vote.
On Sunday, two surveys conducted at the exit of the polling offices and a census carried out by a civil society have both proved the huge superiority of the "yes" votes with a ratio of 63% and 70% respectively.
Rafael Correa, by the way, talked about the victory of his draft constitution on the night from Sunday to Monday.
"The Constitution has won an overwhelming victory," he said, and he thanked the Ecuadorians at the governor's seat in Guayaquil, which is 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As is well known, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez, Morales and Chilean president Michelle Bachelet.
According to a report from the observation mission of the Organization of the United States of America (OAS), the vote took place in a calm atmosphere. Its main theme was a 444-point text that summarized the principles of "new socialism" protected by the President.
The proposed constitution places state power at the service of the economy, while maintaining the right to "plan development" for a country which essentially lives from oil extraction by foreign companies and foreign currencies sent by immigrants.
The draft constitution of Correa, elected in 2006, also strengthens the power of the head of state, who can obtain seats for up to two consecutive periods and is entitled to disband the Parliament.
Correa has already announced that she intends to take advantage of this opportunity and will compete again in February 2009 for the Head of State mandate.
In addition, the Constitution included the freeness of health services and education.The President has already started to introduce it in his country, which has 13.9 million inhabitants and half of the population lives below the living standards.
Finally, the Constitution prohibits the presence of foreign troops in the country, which could put an end to Quito and Washington's agreement to use the Ecuadorian facility as a basis for US drug control measures.
They freed 19 hostages in Chad.
Egyptian commando ambushed the kidnappers who took 11 tourists and eight escorts ten days ago.
The hostages are now in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts were held for ten days in the desert, from which they were transported unharmed to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
The hostages were released in Chad by an Egyptian commando this morning.
Apparently, in good condition, they arrived by plane at Al Maza military base around 2:30 p.m., which is directly related to the Cairo International Airport.
The hostages were forbidden to make a statement to the press and were immediately transferred to a hospital in Maadi, Cairo’s suburbs, where they were examined.
The hostages are "healthy" and the kidnappers were "no ransom" - said Egyptian Minister of Tourism Zoheir Garanna at the airport.
The hostages were captured on September 19 at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border regions of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, where they took part in an off-road safari.
There were 11 tourists in the group (five Italian men, five German men and one Romanian woman), and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and director of the Aegyptous travel agency.
According to an Egyptian security chief, a 30-member special task force arrived on two helicopters at the scene where the hostage takers were ambushed just before dawn.
"There was a firefight among the troops, half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fled," said the leader asking for his name to be withheld.
He also said that a total of 150 special forces were sent from the Egyptian Lightning Brigade to Sudan, where German and Italian commandos were added.
Italian diplomatic leader Franco Frattini, who is in Belgrade, stressed the role of secret agents and special Italian action groups.
"We must acknowledge that this result could not have been achieved without the professional and effective intervention of our secret service people and our task forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied paying a ransom for the hostages.
The day before, the Sudanese army announced that during patrol they had intercepted an SUV on which the kidnappers were traveling, killing six of them (including the Chadian leader) and arresting two of them.
According to the military, the hostage takers were associated with a Darfur rebel organization called the Sudanese Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which was immediately refuted by the organization concerned.
