Fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with the applicant, based on people's drug purchase data.
Data protection professionals fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that always requires the use of prescription data to the consent of the person concerned.
This must be in independent hands, otherwise the fox will be entrusted to the henhouse," quotes Richard Dick, the developer of the program for tracking prescriptions, the Washington Post.
Insurance companies shall make the insurance premium and the amount due in the event of an accident dependent on the health status of the applicant and shall not make insurance with it if they consider the risk to be too high.
They used to send him for medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the light of the results of the investigation.
Dick came up with a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: from pharmacies, based on the customer's identification number, he easily acquires what drugs he has purchased in the last year and a half, and the program itself concludes what disease he is suffering from and what his health status is.
For example, if you regularly take high doses of cholesterol, it suggests that you have virtually uncontrolled levels of fat in your blood, which immediately places you in a higher risk category.
Several versions of the programme are in circulation, some of them also set a risk multiplier, so the insurance company has little to do but paperwork, although small difficulties arise.
The disadvantages are that some medicines can be used for multiple purposes, for example, some substances can be used against migraines or hot flushes, but are also effective against depression.
The latter is a significant risk-raising factor for business insurers and not the former.
To obtain and process the data, separate companies were formed, and before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, they asked the patient for his consent.
They are now bound by the authorities, although no penalty has been imposed for their failure to do so.
Some companies have been processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to drug consumption data so that they can provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and the use control will be increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate health data protection law, but its scope applies only to healthcare providers and insurers.
Before the convention, there is a bill that gives authorities control over companies specialising in providing information.
Dick Richard realizes that this is not enough: he has therefore improved his programme, which would be linked to the explicit consent of the data subject.
Another question is that the person concerned may hardly refuse to consent, otherwise the insurers will not sign a contract with him.
So the hens are somehow dependent on the fox's favor.
