They found the plane of the missing billionaire Steve Fossett a year ago.
They found the remains of the billionaire Steve Fossett's plane, who disappeared over the Nevada desert on September 3rd, 2007.
The wreckage was found on a 3,000-metre high plateau near Mammoth Lakes, in the Sierra Nevada Mountains on the border between California and Nevada.
No human remains were found inside the plane.
John Anderson, the sheriff of Madera County, dispelled all remaining doubts: "After determining the location of the plane, we sent out a team, and now we can be sure it's the plane that Steve Fossett flew on the day of his disappearance," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff also confirmed that there were no human remains found in the aircraft or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Department of Transport Safety (NTSB) stated that a commission of inquiry was requested a few hours after the discovery of the wreck, which was able to identify the plane and determine that it really was the Bellanca 8kcab that disappeared on September 3, 2007, the day Fossett from Yerington, Nevada, took a three-hour flight.
Yesterday in California, near the Nevada border, a couple found some of Fossett's personal effects near his home in Mammoth Lakes.
Two Fosset IDs issued by the Illinois FAA, some cash and a sweater.
The search for Fossett was abandoned a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire has set up a number of peaks that he used to write himself into history.
